@startuml gear_input_to_tcu_shift_slip_signal_flow
!theme plain
skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center
skinparam responseMessageBelowArrow true

title Gear Input To TCU Shift Slip Signal Flow\n(gear input + mode/speed context -> TCU shift-slip publication)

participant "Gear source\nGearInput / GearState" as Gear #E8F0FE
participant "VCU\nDriveMode / PowertrainState" as VCU #E8F7E8
participant "Vehicle state\nVehicleSpeed" as Veh #F4F7FB
participant "TCU\ntransmission owner" as TCU #FFF4CC
participant "Transmission observers" as Obs #FCE8FF

== Shift-Slip Inputs ==

Gear -> TCU : frmGearStateMsg\nGearInput / GearState
VCU -> TCU : frmVehicleModeMsg\nDriveMode / PowertrainState
Veh -> TCU : frmVehicleStateCanMsg\nVehicleSpeed
activate TCU
TCU -> TCU : normalize stale inputs
TCU -> TCU : detect gear transition against\nlast gear state
TCU -> TCU : derive ShiftState / ShiftTargetGear / ShiftSlip
TCU -> TCU : update ShiftCounter and clutch temperature
note right of TCU
Representative outputs
- ShiftState
- ShiftTargetGear
- ShiftSlip
- ClutchTemp
end note

== Shift Publish ==

TCU -> Obs : frmTransShiftStateMsg
TCU -> Obs : frmTransmissionTempMsg
deactivate TCU

note over Gear, Obs
Representative runtime chain
1. Gear input change reaches TCU
2. TCU combines it with drive-mode and speed context
3. TCU detects active shift transition and computes shift slip
4. Transmission observers verify shift-state progression
end note

@enduml
